# Stable Matching with Contingent Priorities — Simulation Code

This directory contains the simulation code for the paper *"Stable Matching with Contingent Priorities"*, which studies school choice mechanisms that promote joint sibling assignment using data from the Chilean school choice system.

The code reproduces all numerical results in the paper (Tables 1–3 and the appendix tables) and supports running additional comparisons against the new family-aware heuristics introduced in the companion paper.

---

## Quick start

Reproduce the main paper results (Table 1, Magallanes 2023) with 100 simulations on 8 cores:

```bash
python new_simulations.py
```

Run on a server without losing progress on disconnect:

```bash
nohup python new_simulations.py > run.log 2>&1 &
tail -f run.log    # monitor progress
```

---

## Directory contents

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `generate_inputs.py` | Reads instance files; draws lotteries (STB, MTB, STB-F, MTB-F); writes instances from raw CSV data |
| `algorithms.py` | Deferred Acceptance (`DA`) and the sequential heuristics `Descending` (current Chilean practice, §5.2.2) and `Ascending` (Appendix D.3) |
| `solve_opt.py` | Gurobi formulations: `AbsoluteHard`, `AbsoluteSoft`, `PartialHard`, `PartialSoft`, `MaxSiblings` (FOSM), `NoSiblings` (SOSM), and the no-tie-breaker variants `AbsoluteHardNTB`, `DescendingNTB` |
| `mechanisms.py` | New family-aware heuristics from the companion paper: `plain_DA`, `FSD_U`, `SF_Reserve`, `SF_SD`, `SF_DA`, `SF_AP_DA`, `FSD`, `FSD_A` |
| `family_preferences.py` | Utilities to inspect family preference structure (consistency with master orderings, etc.) |
| `simulations.py` | Original simulation driver from the paper (Tables 1–3 reproduction) |
| `new_simulations.py` | Extended simulation driver comparing paper benchmarks against new heuristics |

---

## Setup

### Requirements

- Python 3.8+
- `numpy`, `pandas`
- `gurobipy` with a valid Gurobi license (academic licenses are free at [gurobi.com/academia](https://www.gurobi.com/academia/academic-program-and-licenses/))

```bash
pip install numpy pandas gurobipy
```

### Expected directory structure

The simulation scripts expect input data one level above the code directory:

```
project_root/
├── code/                       # this directory
│   ├── generate_inputs.py
│   ├── algorithms.py
│   ├── solve_opt.py
│   ├── new_simulations.py
│   └── ...
├── R/
│   └── intermediate_data/      # input instances live here
│       ├── Magallanes/
│       │   └── 2023/
│       │       └── instance.txt
│       ├── OHiggins/
│       └── ...
└── outputs/                    # results are written here
    └── new_simulations/
```

Available regions (subject to your data):
- `Magallanes` (main paper region)
- `OHiggins`, `Atacama`, `Coquimbo`, `LosLagos`, `Tarapaca`, `Antofagasta`, `Arica`, `Rios` (robustness)

If your `instance.txt` files are missing, generate them first by running `generate_inputs.write_instance_from_csv(indir, outdir, tie_breaker, year)` on the raw CSV data.

---

## Running simulations

### The two drivers

- **`simulations.py`** reproduces Tables 1–3 of the paper exactly. Use this if you want the published numbers.
- **`new_simulations.py`** is the recommended entry point for new experiments. It compares paper benchmarks against the heuristics in `mechanisms.py` and produces a single combined LaTeX table.

### Configuring `new_simulations.py`

Edit the `__main__` block at the bottom of the file:

```python
if __name__ == "__main__":
    REGION = "Magallanes"
    YEAR = 2023
    TIE_BREAKER = "mtbf"
    NUM_SIMS = 100
    NUM_CORES = 8

    METHODS = [
        # Paper benchmarks
        "SOSM", "FOSM", "Descending", "Ascending",
        "Soft", "Hard", "Hybrid-310", "Hybrid-320", "Hard-NTB",
        # New heuristics
        "DA", "FSD-U", "SF-Reserve", "SF-SD", "SF-DA", "SF-AP-DA", "FSD", "FSD-A",
    ]

    run_simulations(
        region=REGION, year=YEAR, tie_breaker=TIE_BREAKER,
        num_sims=NUM_SIMS, num_cores=NUM_CORES, methods=METHODS,
    )
```

### Available methods

**Benchmark methods** (from the paper):

| Name | Description | Reference |
|---|---|---|
| `SOSM` | Student-Optimal Stable Matching (DA, no sibling priorities) | Gale-Shapley |
| `FOSM` | Family-Optimal Stable Matching (max siblings together) | §3 |
| `Descending` | Sequential DA, 12th grade → Pre-K (current Chilean practice) | §5.2.2 |
| `Ascending` | Sequential DA, Pre-K → 12th grade | Appendix D.3 |
| `Hard` | Absolute-Hard IP (Formulation 21) | §4.1, Table 1 |
| `Soft` | Absolute-Soft IP (always feasible) | §5.3, Table 1 |
| `Hybrid-310` | Absolute-Hybrid with ζ=310 (best feasible-100% point) | §5.3.1, Table 2 |
| `Hybrid-320` | Absolute-Hybrid with ζ=320 (higher sibs together, ~80% feasible) | Table 2 |
| `Hard-NTB` | Absolute-Hard without initial lotteries | Appendix E.2.2, Table 3 |

**New heuristics** (from `mechanisms.py`):

| Name | Description |
|---|---|
| `DA` | Plain DA with sibling priorities |
| `FSD-U` | Family Serial Dictatorship — unstructured |
| `SF-Reserve` | Siblings-First with reserved seats |
| `SF-SD` | Siblings-First Serial Dictatorship |
| `SF-DA` | Siblings-First Deferred Acceptance |
| `SF-AP-DA` | Siblings-First Active-Priority DA |
| `FSD` | Family Serial Dictatorship (greedy) |
| `FSD-A` | Family Serial Dictatorship (active priorities) |

### Tie-breaker options

Set `TIE_BREAKER` to one of:

- `"mtb"` — Multiple Tie-Breaking (each school has its own lottery)
- `"mtbf"` — MTB at the family level (siblings get correlated draws across schools) — **paper default**
- `"stb"` — Single Tie-Breaking (one global lottery for all schools)
- `"stbf"` — STB at the family level

Tables 1–3 of the paper all use `"mtbf"`. Appendix D.3 reports robustness under `"mtb"` and `"stb"`.

---

## Running on a server

### Keeping the job alive

Three options, in order of recommended use:

**1. tmux (best for interactive monitoring):**

```bash
tmux new -s sims
python new_simulations.py
# detach: Ctrl+B then D
# reattach: tmux attach -t sims
```

**2. nohup (simplest fire-and-forget):**

```bash
nohup python new_simulations.py > run.log 2>&1 &
tail -f run.log              # monitor
pkill -f new_simulations.py  # kill if needed
```

**3. screen** — same idea as tmux if tmux is not installed.

### Parallelization

The script parallelizes **across simulations** using Python `multiprocessing`. With `NUM_CORES=8` and `NUM_SIMS=100`, you have 8 sims running concurrently on 8 cores; within each sim, methods run sequentially.

**To avoid Gurobi oversubscribing cores**, edit `solve_opt.py` and set `Threads=1` on every Gurobi model. Otherwise each sim's Gurobi solve grabs 4 threads, and 8 × 4 = 32 threads compete for fewer physical cores. With `Threads=1` and `NUM_CORES=8`, you cleanly use 8 physical cores end-to-end.

### Multiple regions

Run regions sequentially inside one script:

```python
for region in ["Magallanes", "Atacama", "OHiggins", "LosLagos"]:
    run_simulations(region=region, year=2023, tie_breaker="mtbf",
                    num_sims=100, num_cores=8, methods=METHODS)
```

Or in parallel processes if you have enough cores (e.g. 32+ cores → 4 regions × 8 cores each):

```bash
nohup python new_simulations.py --region Magallanes --num_cores 8 > log_M.txt 2>&1 &
nohup python new_simulations.py --region Atacama    --num_cores 8 > log_A.txt 2>&1 &
```

(Requires adding `argparse` to the `__main__` block — see the parallelization section in the project notes.)

### Runtime estimates

Per sim, on the Magallanes 2023 instance:
- Heuristics (`SOSM`, `Descending`, `Ascending`, all `mechanisms.py` methods): seconds
- IP solves (`Hard`, `Soft`, `Hybrid-*`, `Hard-NTB`, `FOSM`): ~10–20 s each

For a full Magallanes run with 100 sims, all methods, on 8 cores: roughly **2 hours**. Larger regions (OHiggins, LosLagos): **3–6 hours**.

---

## Outputs

Results are written to `../outputs/new_simulations/`:

| File | Contents |
|---|---|
| `{region}_{year}_{tb}_raw_{N}sims.csv` | One row per (sim, method) pair — every individual result |
| `{region}_{year}_{tb}_summary_{N}sims.csv` | One row per method — means and standard errors across sims |
| `{region}_{year}_{tb}_table_{N}sims.tex` | LaTeX file with two tables (main comparison + additional metrics), ready to `\input{}` |

Reported statistics include: number of solved instances, average preference of matched students, top-preference assignments, unassigned students, siblings together, and the three separation categories from the paper (separated-none, separated-one, separated-both), plus singleton/sibling breakdowns.

